tip.text:
We lament the fall of the tram as much as the next app, but that cloud has a silver lining because the old Clapton Tram Depot has been superbly converted into a soothing, beautiful café full of botany, exposed brickwork, ancient beams and parquetry flooring. The owners of this place have really put some time into the aesthetic and we're digging it. They serve breakfast, lunch and also sell a range of organic products from this light-filled space.

Whilst the lunch menu features a couple of toasted sandwiches and a soup of the day, we stopped by for a lazy breakfast where the menu comes with all the classics: Bloody Mary, sourdough, granola, eggs, bacon. Whatever you do, though, get a dish featuring their portobello mushrooms in tarragon and soya cashew cream - you won't regret it. With soft piano music playing overhead, and locals reading the paper and having a chat, this is a green oasis of calm in Clapton.

Sure you've been in your fair share of cafes, but not one quite like this. Owner Aidan, an avid collector and lover of all things natural history, has lovingly (and painstakingly) created a cafe-cum-miniature-natural-history-museum and it's a transportive, singular experience - as close to the cupboard-into-Narnia flex as it's possible to get. From the luxey pastel pink and creme hues; to the foraged branches and moss; to the surreal taxidermy sitting proud, it's an aesthetic rarity - and a reminder that sometimes fetishes can be a good thing.

With the layout of a small gallery, glass cabinets are filled with all manner of fossils, bones, artefacts and specimens. All for sale; all worthy of a momentary browse. And if that tummy starts to rumble, you'll find coffees, cakes and a short breakfast and lunch menu with carefully put together dishes such as Ottolenghi home-baked beans, salsa and beetroot yoghurt on sourdough; manchego and cheddar toastie with truffle oil; or slow roasted garlic and thyme mushrooms on toast. Keep an eye out for a cute garden out back too.

It’s hard to sum up how much we rate this place - we even considered keeping it a secret, until we remembered the main purpose of our employment. In a space perfectly utilising the edgy-industrial surrounds of the railway arch it finds itself in, you'll find an audio-lounge, restaurant (with changing kitchen residencies), vinyl store and art bookshop.

While away the hours sipping on a something at the bar; nodding your nut at a Saturday record shop in-store from in-house record label BBE; or tucking into something delicious from their low-lit, chic restaurant space. You get the sense that this is more of a passion project than a flagrant money-maker - it's often fairly tranquil and we get the feeling that's how they like it. Oops.

This industrial-chic lounge bar and restaurant may look out of your wallet’s league, but on opening the menu you'll be in for a nice surprise.

Serving great value lunches (try the grilled mackerel salad with fennel and apple slaw for £7), dinners and cocktails around the clock, this is the kind of neighbourhood place you'll find yourself nipping back to regularly. It was the classic Tom Collins-inspired drinks menu with over 40 variations that got our heads turnings - go for the Cognac Blazer Collins for all the tastes of Christmas in one glass, minus the turkey.

Formerly the rather ramshackle London Fields Pub, this building has had a significant refurb to become Martello Hall: a three storey townhouse that serves as a cocktail bar, restaurant, workspace and on-the-go coffeehouse. Plenty of dough has been spent on the stripped-back decor and vintage furniture, and the result is a pretty swanky and classy joint.

Food wise, it's mostly Italian fare with sharing plates and a wood fire oven for delicious pizzas. We'd particularly recommend the Number 7, with roast squash & beetroot, ricotta, hazelnuts, beetroot pesto, mint and kale. Upstairs, you'll find a cosy lounge area with decks and a cocktail bar, which seems an ideal place to woo and be wooed as the night unfolds.

What else? You can hot desk here and work, and also grab coffee or sausage roll by the inch from their street hatch.

If there was any doubt about the level of cash being splashed in London Fields, Mare Street Market is the definitive proof. In a huge, ornately decorated space, this is a curated 'best of' selection of Hackney businesses: coffee from Flying Horse Coffee; (expensive) flowers from Rebel Rebel; vinyl from Stranger Than Paradise records; a rotating pop up shop selling something artisan and expensive; an antique furniture shop; a deli; and both an open kitchen and restaurant.

With all that under one roof, this is most certainly set to become a blue-tick-verified Hackney hangout. Not a place to come if you're a little strapped, but if you want to sample some top quality produce, see a venue with a super high attention to detail, or just kick it somewhere pleasant, it's definitely worth your time.

London Fields attracts all kinds of cats these days, and plenty of them can be found up on Netil360 roof: a big space offering 360 views, fake grass, plenty of outdoor seating and, come the weekend, lots of hammered sorts wearing sunglasses. Part bar, part cafe and part workspace, this is refreshingly not about exclusivity - it's free to come up and there's a no booking policy on their big tables so you'll need to get here early if you fancy holding down a spot.

The bar does plenty of craft beers and the like - watch out for those £10 pints of Aperol Spritz - whilst Hackney Pizza are in the kitchen serving up fairly decent pizzas to give you something to munch on. This place is really two different animals: midweek, it's a place of creativity and freelancer thinking whilst come the weekend, a wholly different clientele roll on up and make themselves comfortable for the long haul.

The well-loved pop-up Night Tales has taken the leap into brick and mortar to give you NT’s Bar. Make the trek up the several flights of stairs and be greeted to an impressive open plan space adorned with plants and all things millennial. With huge windows and a south-facing roof terrace, this makes for an ideal spot to watch the sunset over the city- cocktail in hand, of course.

Cocktails here are no nonsense - inventive but classy - with all cordials, infusions and shrubs made in house. You might be paying a little more for the view, location and oozin' cool but by George is it worth it.

This little cafe hidden away in Dalston is a real homely affair. Opened by two friends - Nadya Mousawi (Mouse) and Victoria Shard (born de Lotz) - who banded together over their mutual love of good coffee and delicious treats. It kind of feels like they're feeding you from their personal kitchens, and the space definitely exudes flat-living-room vibes. The menu is a simple affair - artisan coffee, scrumptious homemade cakes and creative sandwiches, all done with plenty of love. This is the perfect spot to post up and watch the day drift by.

One of the most popular spots in Stokey, Cafe Z Bar takes serious pride in its Turkish tucker. It's best known for its breakfasts, which include a massive choice of egg options cooked with Turkish sausage, feta cheese and other primo additions.

In the evening, the menu opens up even more - fish kebabs, Middle Eastern lamb meatballs, and even a range of burgers. They also hold supper clubs some evenings, and live music.

This is an example of how to pull off a cafe. Pitched up on a serene corner of the industrial lands of Walthamstow, Lighthaus is a community hotspot for its super friendly staff, charming, light-filled interiors and tasty food. The huge windows let plenty of rays through, basking the chic interiors and soothing greenery in just the right kind of glow - ideal for having a catch-up, remote working or eating something substantial.

They do breakfast and lunch here with aplomb. Their prodigal winter berry porridge keeps regulars coming back, alongside more indulgent treats such as french toast, banana, bacon and yoghurt. Lunch changes daily but is always good quality - bits like parpadelle with fennel sausage ragu, home-made pies, and chicken and kimchee burgers. Our hats are tipped.

As far as authentic live music venues go in London, Cafe OTO takes some beating. Run by the local community, it was named by Vogue Italy as the coolest venue in London a few years back and we're not gonna disagree. With one of the most eclectic line ups about, it hosts big names in the Jazz world whilst also lending the stage to more experimental acts. It makes for an unpretentious and unique vibe. Really, it hits the spot in so many ways.

The wide room and low ceiling make for excellent sound when the room is full whilst Japanese snacks and craft beers are there for consumption. There isn't a raised stage so be careful not to get stuck at the back of the room and you should queue before doors if you are desperate for one of the 100 seats. But for true fans of live music, this is perhaps the pinnacle.

Here we have a cosy charmer of a cafe and daytime restaurant, ideal for doing some filling or some chilling and taking a moment from the metropolis madness. Restored Victorian tiling, mismatched vintage crockery and plenty of worn woods set the backdrop for a homely hangout where locals come in and stay as long as they're reasonably allowed.

Breakfast, brunch and lunch is the game here and the menu is reassuringly straightforward with high-quality ingredients (and the resultant high-ish prices). We went for eggs Benedict with salmon and didn’t regret one single bite. Lunch, meanwhile, is about that large sandwich and salad life, along with more hearty mains such as Scandinavian meatballs or salmon and mackerel fishcakes. Yes, this is a serious foody operation.

When the clock hits brunch in Stokey on weekends, it really fills up, with people nestled in close - so close you might be encouraged to join in a stranger’s conversation or have a bite of their toast. Our advice: don’t.

Whilst most find themselves in Arcola doing the theatre thing, we'd tip you to head to their spacious cafe and bar space to indulge in a bit of grade-A Dalston lounging. This is a calming, creative place to while away the afternoon hours with some coffee and a slice of their banana & nutmeg loaf, maybe pretending to do something on your laptop; maybe reading a book; maybe listening in on other people's conversations.

Once the clock strikes 5pm, it becomes a bar and heats up considerably just before and after showtime. The drinks list is pretty impressive and includes some rare beery treats, with the likes of Redchurch Brewery, East London Brewery, 40ft, and Four Pure all representing. It's also 2 for £10 on a short-list of cocktails. And if you must eat (and you must), check out their warming healthy choices such as a hot vegetarian stew pot or a rissotto burger and fries.

Those Victorians sure had a thing about their ornate features: the parquet floors, the vaulted ceilings, the oak panelling. That all comes together at Bethnal Green Library, one of the nicest spots to get a slice of solitude and get down to business. In a nice looking red-brick building across from the park, this place has beautiful interiors that might just coax something insightful out of you. Might being the key word - it's not a miracle worker.

Split into a few rooms, you really ought to head to the adult library (not that kind of adult) if you want inspo and don't want to feel like you're in a school common room. Here you'll find that curved glass ceiling that you came for and plenty of quiet nooks where you can hide yourself away and be free from distraction. Be warned though: the Wifi system here is notoriously and gloriously complicated.

If someone’s dying wish was ‘to see what that Stoke Newington place is all about’, Esters is the place you’d take them. It’s a neighbourhood joint down a residential street, specialising in many of the prerequisites for a bougie existence: smooth coffees; cakes that could take a stint on the fourth plinth without question; beautiful brunches of seasonal veg, organic eggs and sourdough; and home ‘essentials’ like imported peanut butter and glass coffee percolators. It’s the kind of place where you’ll spend an afternoon picking at a bergamot and poppy seed cupcake whilst trying to figure out what all the regulars did in their previous lives to earn such a nice one this time around.

There is nothing boring about what these guys plate up; sure you'll see some eggs on toast, but were you expecting sourdough with lamb shoulder, fried eggs, white bean puré, cucumber, salted plum and rosemary dressing? How about poached eggs with miso squash, fennel and mint salsa verde? Yeah, we thought not. The glass frontage can get pretty steamy on a Saturday, but what with the period tiles, friendly faces and a vast array of sweet treats, Ester's has a charm we just can't resist.

Ideal for the freelancers of Stokey, this neighbourhood cafe doubles as a work-space hub for small businesses. Grab a table upstairs for all day brunching (of the seasonal type) or a pick from their selection of in house bakes - think walnut, blackberry, and bay loaf and other upmarket treats.

Downstairs you'll find a bunch of seats for all your working needs. Keep it business-like with coffee and fresh croissants, or ease into your evening meetings with a little something from the wine list.

This Haggerston hotspot is a weird one. Part café (of the fry ups variety), part bistro (of the Turkish variety), the place covered in signed photos and messages from famous musicians that have visited the attached recording studio and rehearsal space. It all makes for a strange but comfortable mash up of different cultural motifs.

For food they’re slinging out fry ups and Mediterranean breakfast options alongside some pretty fine kebabs, moussakas and mezze. Or just come and sit with a coffee and see how many musicians on the wall you can name. We got them all, naturally.

You don't have to possess a Japanese child to come to Toconoco, but it certainly isn't frowned upon. This tranquil space, right next to the gently lapping waters of Kingsland Basin, brings some of that much sought after Japanese domesticity via teas, coffees, snacks and lunches. You'll spot plenty of East LDN's Japanese community (sometimes with cute bebe in tow) munching on rice balls, miso soups, soba noodles or their daily special, happy as heck. Or at least that's our impression.

This is a straight-up sanctuary, with plenty of natural light, light woods and simple decor complimenting authentically dope food that makes for a real pleasant lunchtime. Their £7.50 set menu (with a main, rice, miso soup, small salad) is popular, as are their desserts - go for the matcha cheesecake. If you wanna feel that beautiful mixture of zen and full, drop in.

Sure, it's not the kind of place that'll have you reaching for your phone to brag to your pals, but Long White Cloud is a honest and humble cafe that offers two things we like: friendly service and decent fodder. In a long, slightly corridor-feeling white space, they do an all-day brunch selection featuring the usual bits such as a full English, organic scrambled eggs on toast and veggie options. But if you were to sample one thing, it should be the banana bread which comes beautifully toasted with some blueberries strewn across it.
